<subSubSection id="C34B6531FFCA685426F6FF62FD45FF11" box="[151,739,151,178]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BEE36BAFFCA685426F6FF62FD45FF11" blockId="29.[151,739,151,178]" box="[151,739,151,178]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">
<heading id="D0A681D6FFCA685426F6FF62FD45FF11" bold="true" box="[151,739,151,178]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA685426F6FF62FD45FF11" bold="true" box="[151,739,151,178]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">
Conclusions on 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA6854273DFF62FE1AFF12" authorityName="Oken" authorityYear="1817" box="[348,444,151,178]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Stellifer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA6854273DFF62FE1AFF12" bold="true" box="[348,444,151,178]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Stellifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and sciaenid taxonomy
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34B6531FFCA685426F6FF2AFEA7FD6D" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BEE36BAFFCA685426F6FF2AFD7DFE0E" blockId="29.[151,1437,223,717]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">
The subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA68542725FF2AFE6BFF59" baseAuthorityName="Sasaki" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[324,461,223,249]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Stelliferinae">Stelliferinae</taxonomicName>
is unique within 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA685424F7FF2AFCA9FF59" box="[662,783,223,249]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Sciaenidae</taxonomicName>
by having a two-chambered gas bladder and an enlarged pair of lapillus, about the same size as the sagitta. Both characters are also present in the Indo-West Pacific 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA68542324FEF6FA3AFEBD" box="[1349,1436,259,285]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Johnius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA68542324FEF6FA3AFEBD" box="[1349,1436,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Johnius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA685426BBFED2FE90FEE2" box="[218,310,295,322]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Johniini">Johniini</taxonomicName>
) which has a slightly enlarged lapillus but less than one-third the size of the sagitta, they also have an expanded anterior end of the gas bladder (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B4BFFCA6854240EFEBEFD48FEC5" author="Chao, N. L." box="[623,750,331,357]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" pagination="570 - 589" refId="ref19860" refString="Chao, N. L. (1986) A synopsis on zoogeography of Sciaenidae. In: Indo-Pacific Fish Biology. Proceedings of the Second Indo-Pacific Fish Conference, 28 July 28 - 3 August 1985, Tokyo, pp. 570 - 589." type="book chapter" year="1986">Chao 1986</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B4BFFCA6854249BFEBEFC1FFEC5" author="Chao, L. N. &amp; Chang, C. W. &amp; Chen, M. H. &amp; Guo, C. C. &amp; Lin, B. A. &amp; Liou, Y. Y. &amp; Shen, K. N. &amp; Liu, M." box="[762,953,331,357]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" pagination="259 - 270" refId="ref20210" refString="Chao, L. N., Chang, C. W., Chen, M. H., Guo, C. C., Lin, B. A., Liou, Y. Y., Shen, K. N. &amp; Liu, M. (2019) Johnius taiwanensis, a new species of Sciaenidae from the Taiwan Strait, with a key to Johnius species from Chinese waters. Zootaxa, 4651 (2), 259 - 270. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4651.2.3" type="journal article" year="2019">
Chao 
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA6854255DFEB9FCD3FEC5" box="[828,885,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
). Thus, because they are distant in sciaenid phylogeny, their share a last common ancestor dating from the Late Oligocene to Early Miocene expansions (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B4BFFCA68542301FE9AFF51FE0E" author="Lo, P. C. &amp; Liu, S. H. &amp; Chao, N. L. &amp; Nunoo, F. K. E. &amp; Mok, H. K. &amp; Chen, W. J." pageId="29" pageNumber="463" pagination="132 - 143" refId="ref21376" refString="Lo, P. C., Liu, S. H., Chao, N. L., Nunoo, F. K. E., Mok, H. K. &amp; Chen, W. J. (2015) A multi-gene dataset reveals a New World origin and Oligocene diversification of croakers (Perciformes: Sciaenidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 88, 132 - 143. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2015.03.025" type="journal article" year="2015">
Lo 
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA685423E9FE85FF12FE0D" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
), these characters are probably convergent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEE36BAFFCA685426A6FE4DFEA7FD6D" blockId="29.[151,1437,223,717]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">
In this study, we found that 
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA6854279DFE42FDECFE71" box="[508,586,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Stellife</emphasis>
r species (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA68542488FE42FCF9FE71" authorityName="Chao &amp; Carvalho-Filho &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2021" box="[745,863,439,465]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Stellifer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="collettei">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA68542488FE42FCF9FE71" box="[745,863,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">S. collettei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) can show significant geographic variation. Recent studies of Southwestern Atlantic sciaenids, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA685424BBFE2EFBC7FE55" authority="(Marceniuk et al. 2019)" baseAuthorityName="Marceniuk" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[730,1121,475,501]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Bairdiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA685424BBFE2EFCEDFE55" box="[730,843,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Bairdiella</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B4BFFCA6854253BFE2EFBFFFE55" author="Marceniuk, A. P. &amp; Molina, E. G. &amp; Caires, R. A. &amp; Rotundo, M. M. &amp; Wosiacki, W. B. &amp; Oliveira, C." box="[858,1113,475,501]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref21466" refString="Marceniuk, A. P., Molina, E. G., Caires, R. A., Rotundo, M. M., Wosiacki, W. B. &amp; Oliveira, C. (2019) Revision of Bairdiella (Sciaenidae: Perciformes) from the western South Atlantic, with insights into its diversity and biogeography. Neotropical Ichthyology, 17 (1), 1 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / 1982 - 0224 - 20180024" type="journal article" year="2019">
Marceniuk 
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA685425BCFE29FBB0FE55" box="[989,1046,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA6854220CFE2EFEBAFDB9" authority="(Carvalho-Filho et al. 2010)" baseAuthorityName="Carvalho-Filho" baseAuthorityYear="2010" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Macrodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA6854220CFE2EFB47FE55" box="[1133,1249,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Macrodon</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B4BFFCA6854228EFE2EFEB2FDB9" author="Carvalho-Filho, A. &amp; Santos, S. &amp; Sampaio, I." pageId="29" pageNumber="463" pagination="48 - 58" refId="ref19448" refString="Carvalho-Filho, A., Santos, S. &amp; Sampaio, I. (2010) Macrodon atricauda (Gunther, 1880) (Perciformes: Sciaenidae), a valid species from the southwestern Atlantic, with comments on its conservation. Zootaxa, 2519 (1), 48 - 58. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2519.1.3" type="journal article" year="2010">
Carvalho-Filho 
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA685426F6FDF5FF76FDB9" box="[151,208,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA68542749FE0AFD77FDB9" authority="(Marceniuk et al. 2020)" baseAuthorityName="Marceniuk" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[296,721,511,537]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Menticirrhus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA68542749FE0AFE1CFDB9" box="[296,442,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Menticirrhus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B4BFFCA685427A8FE0AFD6FFDB9" author="Marceniuk, A. P. &amp; Caires, R. A. &amp; Rotundo, M. M. &amp; Cerqueira, N. N. C. D. &amp; Siccha-Ramirez, R. &amp; Wosiacki, W. B. &amp; Oliveira, C." box="[457,713,511,537]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" pagination="301 - 333" refId="ref21556" refString="Marceniuk, A. P., Caires, R. A., Rotundo, M. M., Cerqueira, N. N. C. D., Siccha-Ramirez, R., Wosiacki, W. B. &amp; Oliveira, C. (2020) Taxonomic revision of the Menticirrhus americanus (Linnaeus, 1758) and M. littoralis (Holbrook, 1847) (Percomorphacea: Sciaenidae) species complexes from the western Atlantic. Zootaxa, 4822 (3), 301 - 333. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4822.3.1" type="journal article" year="2020">
Marceniuk 
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA6854242DFDF5FD23FDB9" box="[588,645,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA6854256CFE0AFB7BFDB9" authority="(Guimaraes-Costa et al. 2020)" baseAuthorityName="Guimaraes-Costa" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[781,1245,511,537]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Isopisthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA6854256CFE0AFCD9FDB9" box="[781,895,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Isopisthus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B4BFFCA685425EFFE0AFB73FDB9" author="Guimaraes-Costa, A. &amp; Machado, F. S. &amp; Reis-Filho, J. A. &amp; Andrade, M. C. &amp; Araujo, R. G. &amp; Miranda, E. &amp; Sampaio, I. &amp; Giarrizzo, T." box="[910,1237,511,537]" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" pagination="566021" refId="ref20671" refString="Guimaraes-Costa, A., Machado, F. S., Reis-Filho, J. A., Andrade, M. C., Araujo, R. G., Miranda, E., Sampaio, I. &amp; Giarrizzo, T. (2020) DNA Barcoding for the assessment of the taxonomy and conservation status of the fish bycatch of the northern Brazilian shrimp trawl fishery. Frontiers in Marine Science, 7, 566021. https: // doi. org / 10.3389 / fmars. 2020.566021" type="journal article" year="2020">
Guimarães-Costa 
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA6854223AFDF5FB32FDB9" box="[1115,1172,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
have shown that cryptic species are not uncommon. These studies demonstrated that the hidden diversity is often found in species caught as fisheries by-catch, reinforcing the need for detailed studies on taxonomy and zoogeography that can lead to better conservation management. We expect that 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA68542484FD9EFC98FD25" authorityName="Oken" authorityYear="1817" box="[741,830,619,645]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Stellifer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA68542484FD9EFC98FD25" box="[741,830,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Stellifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and widely distributed sciaenids (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA68542294FD99FACDFD26" authorityName="Gill" authorityYear="1861" box="[1269,1387,620,646]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Cynoscion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA68542294FD99FACDFD26" box="[1269,1387,620,646]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Cynoscion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D39FFCA685426F6FD65FEE7FD09" authorityName="Bonaparte in Bonaparte" authorityYear="1831" box="[151,321,656,681]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Micropogonias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="463" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAA8FFCA685426F6FD65FEE7FD09" box="[151,321,656,681]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="463">Micropogonias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) might have similar patterns, when samples become available for further molecular and morphological study.
</paragraph>
